{"/service/ndnp/mnhi/batch_mnhi_ironman_ver02/data/sn90059182/00393341373/1929110801/0399.xml":{"full_text":"nu ELT MDU\nCredit** Real Meaning\nCredit is not so much a trade cour\ntesy extended you as it is an Index\nof your character. When a merchant\nIs willing to \u201ctrust\u201d you. It simply\nmeans that he is willing to discount\nyour reputation for honesty and In\ntegrity.\u2014Grit.\nOPHEUM OULUTH* NOV. 10-11-12\n2. ntWIHTT. 3 MGHTS\nGE\u00b0 EnaraHe\u2014 J\u00bbily\nNew 1* Jk\u00b0\nf XJjp] #\u00aeU\ngFVK I\nw A a w v\nbeauty\nMpCHORUSqf\nMain Floor $3.00-Balconv $3.00 to $2.00\u2014 Gallery SI.OO.\nNOT A MOVING PICTURE!\nTROY\ns The Odorless Dry Cleaners\nPhone 47 for Service.\nCash and Carry Service.\nBranch Office: 34 East Sheridan Street.\nHAMS\u2122\nWe have a large stock of Hams of all the well\nknown brands. All sizes to choose from\u2014and\nthe prices are right. Order a half or a whole\nHam at this market today\u2014you will be satis\nfied with the purchase.\nTelephone No. 52\nSKALA\u2019S\nFRESH MEATS AND GROCERIES\n\"FOR PARTICULAR PEOPLE\"\nEGGS-\nyou can Enjoy\nEggs that come from this store are eggs that\nyou can enjoy\u2014for they are fresh. We guar\nantee them. Place your order today for any\nquantity you wish and we will deliver\npromptly.\nMILLER STORE CO.\nTelephone No. 31.\nSim.pl* Cares far \"Binns*\nDeep breathing is recommended as\na cure for those who get depressed.\nWhen the lungs are properly filleo\nthe brain gets Its full supply of oxy\ngenlzed blood and functions proper\nly. That dispels the depressed feel\nIng.\nA Treasure Worth Guarding\nA good credit standing like a good name is rather to be\nchosen than great riches. It carries with it prestige, influ\nence, confidence, honor, trust, faith and esteem.\nOne cannot afford to sacrifice this essential part of life*\nespecially as it requires so little effort to maintain it.\nAll that is required is to plan according to one's income\n\u2014the modern phrase is, \u201cbudgeting one's expenditures.* 9\nIn making purchases on a credit basis one should always\nhave in mind: \u201cWill our income justify this, and leave\nus in a position to pay this obligation when due?\u201d\nThis is offered as a suggestion in an effort to aid indi\nviduals in this community to maintain a high credit stand\ning, one of the most valuable assets any one can possess.\nMINING ANO STEEL\nRELATIONS GOOD\n(Skillings Mining Review.)\nThe visit to the Lake Superior iron\ndistrict by officials of Pickands, Math\ner Co., Bethlehem Steel, Youngs\ntown Sheet and Tube and the By-\nProducts Coal Company, of last week\nis a furthur reminder of the intimate\nrelations existing between the mining\ninterests of the district and of the\ngreat steel industry of the United\nStates.\nEvery season, and frequently, the at\ntention of the people of this greatest of\nall iron ore districts is called to this\nrelation, which has been so long main\ntained, which has witnessed phenom\nenal growth both in the production and\nconsumption of iron ore, by the visits\nof executives to inspect the respective\ngroups of mines. Always Duluth is a\ngeneral objective, since several of the\nlarge mining companies maintain their\ngeneral operating headquarters here.\nThe operations of the mining interests\nof the ore consuming industry in the\nLake Superior district directly main\ntain many thousands of men and their\nfamilies, and while it has been pointed\nout in some quarters that machinery\nhas reduced somewhat the number of\nmen employed, the fact is obvious that\nwithout the introduction of Uu modern,\nheavy equipment that the production\nand shipment of 65,000,000 tons this\nseason would have been quite impos\nsible. Machinery, like advertising, is\na subtle force. It also creates em\nployment. The ultimate result is\nprogress, and new comforts lor million*\nwho otherwise could not afford them.\nThat is something which is obvious to\neverybody.\nZenith Furnace\nThe visit of the officials of Pickands.\nMather Co., every year carries spec\nial interest to Duluth people, for they,\nlike the Steel Corporation, have a large\nand successful local interest in this\ncommunity, in the Zenith Furnace Co.\nFor years this interest has existed, and\nhas been known by many, but for some\nreason has never been given the prom\ninence locally that it deserves Plenty\nof Duluth people do not know it at all\nBut officials of Pickands, Mather Co.\nare heavily interested in the Zenith\nFurnace Company. This fact was a\nsubject of conversation at the Kitchi\nGammi Club last week when the vis\nitors nere. \"Yes, it is true and we are\nproud of it,\" said H G. Dalton, and he\nbeamed upon W. B. Castle of Duluth,\npesident of the Zenith Furnace Com\npany, who came up to the goup in\nat that moment.\nThe views of the men actively en\ngaged in large enterprises are always\nsought as regards the future of bus\niness and industry, a natural con\nsequence, for they, better than any\nbody else, are in constant touch with\nthe elements which make for constant\nprosperity. If there is a cloud on the\nhorizon no bigger than a man\u2019s hand\nthey are presumed to be able to detect\nit with the naked eye. They, and not\nthe professional forecasters are the\nreal weather prophets of the times.\nIt is gratifying to relate that the vis\nitors in Duluth last week were in a con\nfident frame of mind regarding the\nfuture. While stock prices were crash\ning; to which no reference even was\nGood Credit is a Golden Possession\nLet Your Account Be Appreciated\nNot Merely Tolerated\nmade, and was presumed to have no\nbearing, they uttered expressions of\noptimism\n\u201cI take a confident view of the out\nlook for business and industry,\u201d said\nH. C. Dalton of Pickands, Mather\nCo- \u201cI see nothing in the situation to\ncause apprehension,\u201d he added.\nTo the same inquiry, addressed to C.\nS. Robinson, vice-president of Youngs\ntown Sheet Tube, he replied that the\nexisting conditions present no sugges\ntion of any radical change. He seemed\nmildly surpised that anybody seemed to\nthink it worth while to bring the sub\nject up.\nElton Hoyt, Il's interview as to fund\namental conditions and sustained good\ntimes may be summed up in four\nwords: \u201cI am an optimist.\u201d He is one\nof the Cleveland officials of Pickands,\nMather Co., who makes rather fre\nquent visits to Duluth and other points\nin the Lake Superior iron ore district.\nW. L. Cummings, who is chief geol\nogist and mining engineer for the\nBethlehem Steel Corporation, and who\nis widely known in the mining industry,\ntook refuge behind the fact that he is\nstrictly a professional man but he in\ntimated very clearly that he has no\nticed no blemishes in the situation.\nWhile the expressed views of the\ncaptains of industry is in no way a\ndefense of the times and underlying\nconditions, their confidence is never\ntheless re-assuring. The recent break\nin the stock market was the result of\noverbought conditions, and contrary to\nthe views of some, has no hearing at\nthis time on an approach of a general\nlet-down for an indefinite period of\nbusiness and industry. When such\ntime comes it will be quite generally\nrecognized.\nThe Eastern members of the party\ninclude: C. S. Robinson, vice-president\nof the Youngstown Sheet Tube Co.,\nGlen Heedy, assistant to the vice-pres\nident of he Youngstown company, W-\nL. Cummings of the Bethlehem Steel\nCorp., H. G. Dalton, Elton Hoyt, IL\nW. A. Rose, Pick and r Mather Co.,\nand C. D. Caldwell, president of the\nBy-Products Coke company of Chi\ncago.\nLake Superior officials of Pickands\nMather Co., include W. P. chinr,\nDuluth, gentral manager; W. P Bots\nford, Hibbing, and A. D. Chisholm,\nIronwood, Mich, assistant general\nmanager; W. EL Gallagher, Jr., Dul\nuth, chief electrical and mechanical\nengineer, and J. C. Metcalf, Duluth,\nchief mining engineer\nSecond Largest Operator\nNext to the Oliver Iron Mining Co.,\nthe mining division of the United\nStates steel Corporation, Pickands,\nMather Co. is the largest operator\nin the Lake Superior iron ore district.\nIt has 31 mines in operation and is\nemploying 3600 men The Interiake\nSteamship Company is controlled by\nPickands, Mather A Co. There are 49\ncargo ships in the fleet, the second\nlargest on the Great Lakes.\nPickands, Mather Co- win have a\nrecord ore movement this season of\nabout 14,000,000 gross tons.\nOne peculiarity of the port of Loa\ndon is the extent to which vessel\nload from and discharge into barges\nLondon Is a barging port, and it is a\nstaggering fact that on the\nare 10,000 barges, continually plying\nto and from the docks and the\nwharves, warehouses, and factories\nwhich line ita 170 miles of tidal\nbanks.\nelt, Minnesota.\nBusiness Outlook Good\nPort Barges Kept Busy\nx \u2019\u2019W-\nV\n'\u25a0\u25a0s\nATHLETICS\nBy Charles Gallagher\nEly Trounced by Falls Eleven\nThe Ely high school football team,\nwho a week ago trounced Two Har\nbors, suffered one of its severest set\nbacks in recent years last week when\nthey fell before the strong Interna\ntional Falls eleven by a 34 to 0 score.\nRagged, football and the loss of two\nlinemen through ineligibility cost Ely\nanother conference defeat Ely was\nfar from the form displayed in down\ning the Harbors eleven and except for\nthe third period the Falls eleven were\ncomplete masters of the game. Only\nin the third period were the local boys\nable to hold their opponents on equal\nterms as the Falls eleven scored one\ntouchdown in the first quarter and two\nin each of the second and fourth\nperiods\nDespite the loss, Capt. Nicholas at\nquarter and Lindy at tackle, the team\nplayed great football at times. Capt.\nNicholas broke away on another of his\nbrilliant runs and crossed the Falls\ngoal, but the officials called the play\nback declaring be had been stopped\nby an opposing tacklfer.\nIt looks, according to the score, as\nif International Falls may be able to\nproduce another Nagurski and Somers\nin the person of Formick at fullback\nand Scheela at quarter. The lineup\nand summary follows:\nEly (0) International Falls (34)\nBanovitz le.\nLindy\nJohnsonlg Burton\nLobe\nRozman rg Koski\nGrahekrt Corrin\nSmrekarre Masters\nNichol .qb Scheela\nZgonc\nRiikolarh Lindvall\nKrall\nTomorrow the local eleven will close\nits season with Tower when the two\nteams will battle for the Vermilion\nrange championship. Tower has yet\nto secure a victory over the Ely boys\nbut this year they have a powerful\nteam and are given a good chance to\nwin. Ely must win this game to get\nan even break in their schedule as\nthey have only three victories as com\npared to four defeats.\nFour boys win be making a strong\nbid for all range laurels in this game\nand their playing is expected to be the\nhighlghts of the game- They are\nCapt. Nicholas at quarter and Lindy\nat tackle for Ely and Capt Tekautz at\nfullback and Swanson at center for\nTower.\nFive of the Ely boys win dose their\ngrid career with the local high school\ntMs year. They are Capt. Nicholas\nand Lindy, four year letter men.\nZgonc and Banovetz, two year letter\nmen jand Bmrekar.\nEly Coach Brings Morgan Park Its\nFirst Championship\nHarold Chinn, former Ely athlete,\nand dow coach of the Morgan Park\nHigh of Duluth, in Us first year there\nWrought the school its first champkm\nshipa. Altbo the Morgans were tied\nfor three rhsnipifwwhips it is the first\ntime the school has won any of these\nhonors. Morgan Park with two vic\ntorias and one defeat tied Central and\n..It Withrow\n.Ih\n..fb\nCathedral for the Duluth City Cham\npionship, and with five victories and\na defeat tied these two teams and\nSuperior Central for the head of the\nlakes conference honors- In the\neighth district Minnesota high school\nconference they were tied with Dul\nuth Central for top honors with four\nvictories and a defeat.\nDuluth Central defeated Morgan\nPark 6 to 0 in its only setback of the\nseason, while Morgan Park downed\nCathedral 7 to 0, who in turn downed\nCentral by an 8 to 7 score to tie for\nthe championships.\nThis was the moat successful season\nin the school\u2019s history, and it took an\nEly coach to bring it to them. This\nis Chinn\u2019s first year as a high school\ncoach and he has turned in a very\ncreditable showing.\n\u201cWHERE THERE\u2019S A WILL\u2014\u201d\nTHERE\u2019S MANY AN ODDITY\nHave you made your win yet? Near-\nIT win\nshow 82% increase\nFacts just obtained from 28 representative American\ncities indicate conclusively that the motoring public\nprefers the Eight to all other engine types. Take the\nTwin Cities as an example: for the first eight months\nof 1929, new cars with list prices above SIOOO showed\nan 82 per cent increase in Eights and a 12 per cent\ndecrease in Sixes!\nAt the famous Paris Salon this fall, 4.4 makes of eight cyl\ninder cars were exhibited, compared with 2 7 last year.\nStudebaker, world\u2019s largest producer of Eights, two yean\nago initiated this era of the inexpensive Eight with the cham\npion Studebaker President which traveled 30,000 miles in\n26,326 consecutive minutes.\nAnd today, at customary six-cylinder prices, you can\nchoose from three great lines of Studebaker Eights holders\nof eleven world records for speed and endurance and more\nAmerican stock car records than all other makes combined.\nGet a smart, new, thrifty Studebaker Eight backed by\n577 years of manufacturing integrity and your car will be\nworth more in the trade-in markets of the future.\nTUDEBAKER\ny g [f Dictator Eight Sedan *1285\nCommander Eight Sedan \u2019ISIS\nVVJ S p resident Eight Sedan *1765\nFatr-Dttr Stefan M net eb. Prime at thtfaOnry\nROY BAXTRUM, Dealer\nEveready Model 52 \u2014\u2022157.50 without tubes\nJFitA bauit-tM speak*\nVARIOMETER\nEVEREADY SCREEN-GRID\nEVEREADY Screen-Grid tuning system combines one\nvariometer and three variable condensers, operated by\na single knob. By co-ordinating these two different\nkinds of tuning devices, Eveready gives you the out\nstanding advantages of each. The most scientifically\ncorrect arrangement, giving yon a newly perfected per\nform\nfora\nJOSEPH MANTEL\nHardware-Furniture\nPhone 56. R. Ely, Minnesota.\nRADIO RECEIVERS\no-4 spyHsMi.\u2014 of KA aa4\nly everybody has and\nour doing it, the psychologists Ml us,\nis that it's the best way in which we\ncan perpetuate ourselves after we have\nfinished with this life. Queer bmosn\ndocuments\u2014many of these \u201clast feMa\nments.\u201d They reveal, as do nothing\nelse which man writes his better side\nand his worse side. And they reveal\nalso some queer quirks in human\nnature.\nIn this issue of The Miner appears\nan illustrated feature article by Elmo\nScott Watson which tells the interes\nting stories of some queer wlHa Be\nsure to read \u201cWhere There\u2019s a Will\u2014\u201d\nin this issue.\nThe \u201cm\" in the word comptroller\nhas the sound of \u201cn.\u201d This is the\nusual official spelling, but originated\nin a false derivation from compt She\n\u201cp\u201d is silent\nEights\nIN NEW\nRECEIVER\nsensitivity and selectivity. Come i*\ni that will amaze you\u2014 today 1\neve\u00dfEAdy\n\u25bc\u2022AM MMM MGtrrUC*\n8, UHL","height":"28668","width":"20697"}}
